1
00:00:54,179 --> 00:00:55,805
The chair....

2
00:05:48,806 --> 00:05:50,808
You made it. Come on in.

3
00:05:52,060 --> 00:05:54,645
Picture a reception desk right here.

4
00:05:54,812 --> 00:05:57,815
Right? It's always nice to be greeted
by a friendly face.

5
00:05:57,982 --> 00:06:01,611
Now, over in this corner,
we got a fireplace.

6
00:06:01,778 --> 00:06:03,946
With a cozy waiting area.

7
00:06:04,113 --> 00:06:06,282
Couch, couple of chairs.

8
00:06:06,449 --> 00:06:07,784
Watercooler.

9
00:06:07,950 --> 00:06:10,787
Electric kettle,
maybe an assortment of teas.

10
00:06:10,953 --> 00:06:13,498
This is my office in here.

11
00:06:13,664 --> 00:06:16,626
Guess what, these are all
original fixtures.

12
00:06:16,793 --> 00:06:18,461
So that's....

13
00:06:19,170 --> 00:06:22,965
We're four blocks from the courthouse.
So how convenient is that?

14
00:06:23,132 --> 00:06:27,428
Now, there's a bathroom,
and it's-- It's cute.

15
00:06:31,933 --> 00:06:33,518
We're gonna get that cleaned out.

16
00:06:33,684 --> 00:06:37,480
There's a shower in there when
you're buried in discovery late at night.

17
00:06:37,647 --> 00:06:39,065
This is for the partner.

18
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:40,775
Corner office.

19
00:06:40,942 --> 00:06:42,735
Lots of natural light.

20
00:06:42,902 --> 00:06:47,156
And that's great
for your circadian rhythms.

21
00:06:48,908 --> 00:06:52,370
Cherry blossoms, that's nice. And....

22
00:06:53,538 --> 00:06:58,126
One, two, three, four, five, six.

23
00:06:58,292 --> 00:06:59,877
It's pretty big.

24
00:07:00,503 --> 00:07:03,589
There's a kitchenette down the hall.

25
00:07:04,507 --> 00:07:09,804
It's kind of perfect for snacks
or BYO lunch.

26
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:14,058
Get one of those snazzy Keurigs,
put that in there.

27
00:07:14,225 --> 00:07:17,603
Stick a few potted plants around,
make the place nice.

28
00:07:17,770 --> 00:07:19,605
What do you think?

29
00:07:23,401 --> 00:07:25,403
So no more cell phones?

30
00:07:26,446 --> 00:07:28,865
No, but this is what
the phones were for.

31
00:07:29,031 --> 00:07:32,660
So if you were a lawyer,
this would be a great place, right?

32
00:07:33,244 --> 00:07:35,455
If I was a lawyer...

33
00:07:37,331 --> 00:07:38,416
...nope.

34
00:07:39,125 --> 00:07:41,085
Big glass high-rise.

35
00:07:41,252 --> 00:07:44,255
-Fortieth floor.
-Big glass high-rise?

36
00:07:44,422 --> 00:07:47,091
Yeah, when I'm not on my boat.

37
00:07:48,050 --> 00:07:49,302
All right, Hector...

38
00:07:50,428 --> 00:07:51,429
...is this--?

39
00:07:51,971 --> 00:07:53,139
Is this green?

40
00:07:55,433 --> 00:07:56,767
Is this green?

41
00:08:00,813 --> 00:08:01,814
Excellent, Hector!

42
00:08:05,318 --> 00:08:08,070
Is this person angry?

43
00:08:14,327 --> 00:08:16,245
Is this person happy?

44
00:08:19,081 --> 00:08:22,293
Very good! That was much faster.

45
00:08:22,460 --> 00:08:25,338
Oh, let's just hold off on lunch
for a few minutes.

46
00:08:25,505 --> 00:08:28,466
-Just set the tray on the side.
-Of course, Doctor.

47
00:08:29,842 --> 00:08:32,428
We'll get back to work in just a second.

48
00:08:42,438 --> 00:08:44,649
Sorry, I'll take care of that.

49
00:08:45,441 --> 00:08:48,736
It's okay, Hector.
Just a muscle spasm.

50
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:13,344
Good. Let's continue.

51
00:09:14,762 --> 00:09:16,305
Hector.

52
00:09:17,682 --> 00:09:19,225
Are you with me?

53
00:09:26,232 --> 00:09:27,233
Is this Paris?

54
00:09:34,532 --> 00:09:36,576
Anyone in particular
you want me to talk to?

55
00:09:36,742 --> 00:09:39,287
Or not talk to?

56
00:09:39,537 --> 00:09:41,163
Talk to anyone.

57
00:09:41,330 --> 00:09:43,124
Really, just have fun.

58
00:09:45,793 --> 00:09:48,296
Don't worry. They're gonna love you.

59
00:09:51,757 --> 00:09:54,552
-Yeah, hi. How are you?
-This is Jimmy McGill.

60
00:09:55,136 --> 00:09:57,430
-Nice to meet you.
-Hi. Great to be here.

61
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:59,015
-Ron, this is Jimmy.
-Hi, Ron.

62
00:09:59,181 --> 00:10:02,101
-Hey, Jimmy.
-Gotta say, I'm obsessed with your tie.

63
00:10:02,268 --> 00:10:04,478
Your husband make it?
I didn't see him.

64
00:10:04,645 --> 00:10:07,189
No? Okay. Excuse me one second.

65
00:10:07,356 --> 00:10:11,527
Hey, guys. Jimmy, this is Gary and Stef.
They work on Mesa Verde with me.

66
00:10:11,694 --> 00:10:14,697
The famous Gary
and the famous-er Stef.

67
00:10:14,864 --> 00:10:17,325
Kim says you're the absolute best.

68
00:10:17,491 --> 00:10:20,536
-Ken ate a lot of cake with that.
-Oh, here it is.

69
00:10:20,703 --> 00:10:22,455
This is for us. Debbie, one for you.

70
00:10:22,622 --> 00:10:25,416
-There you go. One for Zack.
-Thank you.

71
00:10:25,583 --> 00:10:26,751
One for Viola.

72
00:10:26,917 --> 00:10:28,711
And you know what?
Two for Lewis...

73
00:10:28,878 --> 00:10:31,631
-...because he skipped lunch to work.
-Really?

74
00:10:56,322 --> 00:11:02,536
One, two, three, four, five, six...

75
00:11:02,870 --> 00:11:07,416
...seven, eight, nine, 10.

76
00:11:32,108 --> 00:11:33,943
Yeah, so.... Yes.

77
00:11:34,110 --> 00:11:37,279
-People don't need theater....
-So was Jill there at the retreat?

78
00:11:39,156 --> 00:11:41,033
-She came later.
-Oh, okay.

79
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:42,952
-I was pretty impressed.
-She was a client.

80
00:11:43,119 --> 00:11:44,453
-Really?
-Oh, yeah.

81
00:11:44,620 --> 00:11:46,163
Do you guys do theater retreats?

82
00:11:46,330 --> 00:11:49,291
No, absolutely not.
Might be a little different this year.

83
00:11:49,458 --> 00:11:51,502
Not sweating with your coworkers.

84
00:11:51,669 --> 00:11:54,797
I heard Packard-Kilber is taking
their whole company to a resort...

85
00:11:54,964 --> 00:11:58,008
...outside of Santa Fe. It's pretty--
Pretty ritzy.

86
00:11:59,093 --> 00:12:01,470
Oh, we're just talking about
company retreats.

87
00:12:01,637 --> 00:12:04,390
That's a great idea.
Where are we going?

88
00:12:04,598 --> 00:12:06,392
Sorry, pal. Employees only.

89
00:12:06,559 --> 00:12:08,227
Oh, darn it.

90
00:12:08,769 --> 00:12:10,646
I'm thinking of splurging this year.

91
00:12:10,813 --> 00:12:13,023
Don't wanna be outdone
by the competition.

92
00:12:13,190 --> 00:12:16,360
You know, word gets out
you're a cheapskate.

93
00:12:16,527 --> 00:12:18,404
Sure, sure. That's hard to shake off.

94
00:12:18,571 --> 00:12:21,866
I've heard Ten Thousand Waves
is supposed to be amazing.

95
00:12:22,032 --> 00:12:23,659
I love that place.

96
00:12:23,826 --> 00:12:26,620
Or Carlsbad Caverns?

97
00:12:26,787 --> 00:12:30,082
I still think Taos is number one.
I'd love a ski trip.

98
00:12:30,249 --> 00:12:33,544
-I think it'd be good for team-building.
-Taos.

99
00:12:33,711 --> 00:12:36,213
That's nice.

100
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:40,718
Feel free to jump in.
We're just spitballing here.

101
00:12:43,846 --> 00:12:46,182
I don't-- I mean....

102
00:12:46,348 --> 00:12:51,061
Well, I mean, if you're up for adventure,
you know where the great skiing is?

103
00:12:51,228 --> 00:12:52,480
Well, it's Telluride.

104
00:12:55,107 --> 00:12:57,234
That's kind of a long drive, isn't it?

105
00:12:58,611 --> 00:13:00,738
That could be part of the fun.

106
00:13:00,905 --> 00:13:04,658
You know, rent one of those
fancy party buses.

107
00:13:05,075 --> 00:13:06,869
Stick  Sound of Music  in the TV...

108
00:13:07,036 --> 00:13:09,205
...everybody sings.
Pretty soon, you're there.

109
00:13:09,371 --> 00:13:11,499
And I gotta say,
the runs in Telluride...

110
00:13:11,665 --> 00:13:14,210
...they make Taos
look like a bunny slope.

111
00:13:14,376 --> 00:13:15,628
Telluride, huh?

112
00:13:16,003 --> 00:13:18,881
-It's worth considering.
-And parkas.

113
00:13:19,048 --> 00:13:21,967
-Everybody's gotta have parkas.
-Of course.

114
00:13:22,134 --> 00:13:24,720
No, I'm talking custom parkas.

115
00:13:25,137 --> 00:13:27,723
Two words: "client development."

116
00:13:27,890 --> 00:13:30,476
They see all of you out there
cutting the powder...

117
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:33,854
...in your matching
Schweikart & Cokely parkas...

118
00:13:34,021 --> 00:13:35,606
...you'll make an impression.

119
00:13:35,773 --> 00:13:37,483
You will thank me later.

120
00:13:38,150 --> 00:13:40,110
You certainly don't think small.

121
00:13:41,862 --> 00:13:45,741
Shit, you know what? Aspen.
Hey, that's where you wanna go.

122
00:13:45,908 --> 00:13:49,203
Aspen is like Telluride on steroids.

123
00:13:49,370 --> 00:13:53,207
You got shopping,
you got restaurants and spas.

124
00:13:53,374 --> 00:13:57,127
Talk about client development,
it's a billionaire's playground.

125
00:13:57,294 --> 00:14:01,173
-Yeah.
-Jimmy, Aspen is like a nine-hour bus ride.

126
00:14:02,550 --> 00:14:04,218
You're right, you're right.

127
00:14:04,385 --> 00:14:08,013
Nine hours, that-- It is a long time
to be sitting on a bus.

128
00:14:08,180 --> 00:14:10,391
-Yes, it is.
-But what's that I hear?

129
00:14:14,436 --> 00:14:17,064
I'm a private-charter jet.

130
00:14:17,231 --> 00:14:19,108
And I'm sorry, I'm very busy right now.

131
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:22,111
I'm transporting 56
distinguished attorneys...

132
00:14:22,278 --> 00:14:27,783
...to their amazing destination.
Aspen, here we come.

133
00:14:28,534 --> 00:14:31,704
Come on, Rich. You're gonna love it.

134
00:14:41,255 --> 00:14:43,382
Well, that was something.

135
00:14:43,757 --> 00:14:45,259
Yup.

136
00:18:00,287 --> 00:18:02,206
He's making progress
on the stroke scale.

137
00:18:02,372 --> 00:18:04,917
He started at a 30,
that number's steadily coming down.

138
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:07,419
He's at a 22 right now.

139
00:18:07,586 --> 00:18:10,297
And he's made modest improvement
in his ataxia.

140
00:18:10,464 --> 00:18:12,966
-Which is loss of--
-Loss of body movement.

141
00:18:13,133 --> 00:18:14,593
Yes.

142
00:18:15,594 --> 00:18:18,555
This all sounds quite positive.

143
00:18:21,058 --> 00:18:25,354
But you know
the question that I will ask.

144
00:18:26,563 --> 00:18:28,190
Is it him?

145
00:18:28,357 --> 00:18:31,235
Is it the Hector Salamanca you knew?

146
00:18:32,861 --> 00:18:36,740
I think, at this point,
that's almost a philosophical question.

147
00:18:36,907 --> 00:18:39,409
What I can tell you
is that he's more responsive.

148
00:18:39,576 --> 00:18:43,122
He's making incremental
improvements almost every day.

149
00:18:44,915 --> 00:18:48,669
I think if you see the evidence,
you'll be very encouraged.

150
00:18:52,005 --> 00:18:55,300
You'll see this was
an especially-productive session.

151
00:19:09,898 --> 00:19:13,443
I know it may seem like
a small thing, that same exchange...

152
00:19:13,610 --> 00:19:15,946
...would've taken four times as long
a month ago.

153
00:19:16,113 --> 00:19:19,408
And a month before that,
he couldn't respond at all.

154
00:19:19,700 --> 00:19:23,036
All his vital signs have improved.

155
00:19:23,203 --> 00:19:26,415
Also, I've been tracking his progress
using the SIS...

156
00:19:26,582 --> 00:19:29,334
...with a particular focus
on hand mobility...

157
00:19:29,501 --> 00:19:31,920
...since that's his mode
of communication.

158
00:19:36,091 --> 00:19:37,885
Has he done that before?

159
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:39,887
The cup?

160
00:19:40,220 --> 00:19:42,681
That was likely
an involuntary movement.

161
00:20:03,619 --> 00:20:05,329
Do you think that was purposeful?

162
00:20:14,296 --> 00:20:16,590
You've done magnificent work.

163
00:20:16,757 --> 00:20:17,841
Thank you.

164
00:20:18,008 --> 00:20:23,013
I understand that construction
on your clinic is nearly complete.

165
00:20:23,180 --> 00:20:25,724
I trust the work
is to your specifications.

166
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:29,978
That's putting it mildly.
The new wing is simply extraordinary.

167
00:20:30,145 --> 00:20:32,940
We'll be able to care for
so many patients...

168
00:20:33,106 --> 00:20:35,651
...who would've been tossed aside.

169
00:20:36,193 --> 00:20:38,779
I've kept you
from your work long enough.

170
00:20:39,238 --> 00:20:42,908
It is time to delegate
Mr. Salamanca's care.

171
00:20:43,075 --> 00:20:46,078
His recovery has been remarkable.

172
00:20:46,245 --> 00:20:49,748
And my gratitude to you
is beyond words.

173
00:20:50,123 --> 00:20:51,667
Are you sure?

174
00:20:51,833 --> 00:20:54,711
Hector's progress is very promising.

175
00:20:54,878 --> 00:20:58,215
With sustained intensive care,
he may eventually learn...

176
00:20:58,382 --> 00:21:02,177
...how to talk and even walk again.

177
00:21:05,264 --> 00:21:07,057
Perhaps...

178
00:21:07,224 --> 00:21:10,185
we should temper our expectations.

179
00:21:12,104 --> 00:21:14,231
I believe the paila marina is ready.

180
00:21:31,123 --> 00:21:34,293
Now that the boys have built
the concrete forms...

181
00:21:34,459 --> 00:21:36,878
...we're nearly ready to pour the walls.

182
00:21:38,130 --> 00:21:40,507
And when's that going to happen?

183
00:21:40,757 --> 00:21:44,094
First, there must be one more blast.

184
00:21:44,261 --> 00:21:46,471
I thought we were done with that.

185
00:21:46,638 --> 00:21:48,015
Almost done, yes.

186
00:21:48,181 --> 00:21:52,436
But we must clear that rock
to make way for the elevator shaft.

187
00:21:52,602 --> 00:21:53,937
Just one more.

188
00:21:54,146 --> 00:21:57,858
Carefully shaped
to keep from damaging the work.

189
00:21:58,025 --> 00:22:01,069
How big a pop are we talking about?

190
00:22:19,755 --> 00:22:22,632
Do you know how long
it's going to take to fix that?

191
00:22:23,091 --> 00:22:26,345
Maybe you like living in this hole,
but we want to go home!

192
00:22:28,889 --> 00:22:30,307
Hey, asshole.

193
00:22:30,891 --> 00:22:33,435
You're not the big boss here.

194
00:22:44,571 --> 00:22:47,199
Boys! Cool it!

195
00:23:08,011 --> 00:23:09,679
Yo, Saul. Three.

196
00:23:10,889 --> 00:23:12,766
Coming right up.

197
00:23:21,400 --> 00:23:23,443
There you go.

198
00:23:27,864 --> 00:23:30,617
-See you.
-Yes, you will.

199
00:23:55,350 --> 00:23:57,310
What can I do you for?

200
00:23:57,477 --> 00:23:59,980
This you? Saul Goodman?

201
00:24:00,147 --> 00:24:02,482
That's right, Officer.

202
00:24:04,025 --> 00:24:06,653
You wanna know where I got it?

203
00:24:07,779 --> 00:24:10,240
Off a drug dealer
who got sprung today...

204
00:24:10,407 --> 00:24:13,660
...because he was using a drop phone
that you sold him.

205
00:24:16,705 --> 00:24:19,499
Doesn't bother you
that you're peddling to lowlifes...

206
00:24:19,666 --> 00:24:21,710
...who use these things to sell drugs?

207
00:24:21,877 --> 00:24:25,130
What my customers do with the phones
after they leave my possession...

208
00:24:25,297 --> 00:24:27,257
...that's their business.

209
00:24:28,258 --> 00:24:30,427
Let me ask you a favor, all right?

210
00:24:30,594 --> 00:24:34,681
Get your van out of here, park in front of
a grocery store in Corrales.

211
00:24:34,848 --> 00:24:37,100
Some place nice, and sell there.

212
00:24:37,267 --> 00:24:39,728
You know, I'm sure there's a lot
of soccer moms...

213
00:24:39,895 --> 00:24:41,563
...that can use some phones.

214
00:24:41,980 --> 00:24:45,775
I don't know. I think my
customer base is right here.

215
00:24:46,234 --> 00:24:49,070
-Get some new customers.
-I don't feel the need to.

216
00:24:49,237 --> 00:24:50,572
See, I got a permit...

217
00:24:50,739 --> 00:24:54,201
...and I'm collecting sales tax
and this is a legitimate business.

218
00:24:54,367 --> 00:24:56,453
So anyone who wants
to buy a phone from me...

219
00:24:56,620 --> 00:24:58,663
-...is free to do so.
-I'm asking nicely.

220
00:24:58,830 --> 00:25:00,707
And I respectfully decline.

221
00:25:01,750 --> 00:25:03,460
-You're going this way?
-There it is.

222
00:25:03,627 --> 00:25:05,587
What'll it be? It's gonna be littering...

223
00:25:05,754 --> 00:25:08,757
...rolling through a stop sign?
How about you plant something...

224
00:25:08,924 --> 00:25:10,926
-...in my glove compartment?
-Take it easy.

225
00:25:11,092 --> 00:25:14,179
Maybe this is why people need privacy,
why they need my phones.

226
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:17,057
-Maybe you're the problem.
-As long as you make a buck...

227
00:25:17,224 --> 00:25:19,184
-...the world can go in the crapper?
-Yeah.

228
00:25:31,613 --> 00:25:32,822
No, no, no. He's a cop.

229
00:25:38,411 --> 00:25:39,496
He's a cop.

230
00:25:48,463 --> 00:25:50,382
This was all just a mistake.

231
00:25:50,549 --> 00:25:53,260
My friend got confused.
He was just trying to do his job.

232
00:25:53,426 --> 00:25:55,637
I hired him for security.
He was protecting me.

233
00:25:55,804 --> 00:25:58,807
You're in plain clothes,
he had no idea you were an officer.

234
00:25:58,974 --> 00:26:00,725
-He knew all right.
-How?

235
00:26:00,892 --> 00:26:02,811
I picked him up three years ago.

236
00:26:03,895 --> 00:26:06,940
-Really?
-Yeah. Pickpocketing.

237
00:26:09,025 --> 00:26:11,987
Wha--? Three years, that's a long time.

238
00:26:12,153 --> 00:26:15,031
I mean, how can you be sure
it's the same guy?

239
00:26:15,198 --> 00:26:17,075
-Seriously?
-Officer, look...

240
00:26:17,242 --> 00:26:18,994
...you were right, I was wrong.

241
00:26:20,412 --> 00:26:21,705
Were you now?

242
00:26:21,871 --> 00:26:23,248
Yes, and you know what else?

243
00:26:23,415 --> 00:26:26,042
You will not see me here
selling my phones ever again.

244
00:26:26,209 --> 00:26:29,421
Right? So just do me a favor,
let's just shake hands...

245
00:26:29,588 --> 00:26:31,881
...avoid the paperwork
and we just go home.

246
00:26:32,048 --> 00:26:33,800
Do you a favor?

247
00:26:33,967 --> 00:26:36,136
I was asking you for a favor.

248
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:38,305
-Fair enough.
-I asked nicely...

249
00:26:38,471 --> 00:26:42,142
...and you told me to go screw myself.

250
00:26:42,559 --> 00:26:45,437
I don't--
I don't think I used those words.

251
00:26:45,604 --> 00:26:47,314
See you around.

252
00:27:29,105 --> 00:27:30,732
Michael.

253
00:27:31,024 --> 00:27:34,402
Glad that you can join me
for my happy hour.

254
00:27:38,239 --> 00:27:40,116
It doesn't look so happy to me.

255
00:27:40,283 --> 00:27:42,702
They'll feel better after...

256
00:27:43,036 --> 00:27:46,331
...how do you say it,
Mittagsschläfchen?

257
00:27:47,207 --> 00:27:51,544
When in kindergarten,
the whole class has a nice little rest.

258
00:27:52,379 --> 00:27:53,588
Nap time.

259
00:27:53,755 --> 00:27:55,215
Nap time.

260
00:27:55,382 --> 00:27:56,758
Good.

261
00:27:56,925 --> 00:27:59,052
Now say,  "Mittagsschläfchen."

262
00:28:00,095 --> 00:28:03,139
-Mittag--
-Mittagsschläfchen.

263
00:28:03,306 --> 00:28:04,766
Mittagsschläfchen.

264
00:28:05,558 --> 00:28:06,976
Good. Good, Michael.

265
00:28:07,143 --> 00:28:09,479
-Pilsner or lager?
-Lager.

266
00:28:09,854 --> 00:28:12,816
Naps are for old farts like you.

267
00:28:14,025 --> 00:28:15,902
And his German...

268
00:28:18,738 --> 00:28:20,323
...sounds stupid.

269
00:28:23,159 --> 00:28:25,620
He said you sound like a real kraut.

270
00:28:27,664 --> 00:28:29,332
How do you say "bullshit"?

271
00:28:30,458 --> 00:28:31,584
"Bullshit."

272
00:28:32,168 --> 00:28:33,712
Yeah, that.

273
00:28:34,754 --> 00:28:37,882
But really,
you're one of us, Michael.

274
00:28:42,554 --> 00:28:46,933
"Ehrmantraut" in German,
it comes from two words.

275
00:28:47,684 --> 00:28:49,853
"World" plus "strength."

276
00:28:50,854 --> 00:28:52,856
Yeah, I guess.

277
00:28:53,022 --> 00:28:54,941
What's the latest?

278
00:28:58,027 --> 00:28:59,362
Before we can continue...

279
00:28:59,529 --> 00:29:03,450
...we must build a new concrete form
and straighten the rebar.

280
00:29:03,742 --> 00:29:05,368
I'm so sorry.

281
00:29:05,535 --> 00:29:08,163
I'm happy to explain the delay
to Mr. Fring.

282
00:29:08,329 --> 00:29:12,500
You don't worry about Mr. Fring.
He just wants to see it done right.

283
00:29:12,959 --> 00:29:16,296
-Let me ask you a question.
-Of course.

284
00:29:17,255 --> 00:29:20,425
What would happen
if we sent Kai back to Germany?

285
00:29:25,847 --> 00:29:27,390
Not good.

286
00:29:27,766 --> 00:29:29,809
Kai is my best demolition man.

287
00:29:30,769 --> 00:29:33,354
Sure, he's a  Großmaul...

288
00:29:33,897 --> 00:29:36,149
...but he's a good boy. They all are.

289
00:29:36,316 --> 00:29:38,985
Maybe that's the problem, they're boys.

290
00:29:39,652 --> 00:29:41,613
Well, yes.

291
00:29:41,780 --> 00:29:45,200
We need young people to do this work.
Or maybe you and I will do it?

292
00:29:45,366 --> 00:29:46,367
No.

293
00:29:48,328 --> 00:29:51,289
They thought they were going
to be here for eight months...

294
00:29:51,456 --> 00:29:55,627
...and they can see
we aren't even halfway done.

295
00:29:55,835 --> 00:29:57,796
You have done
a wonderful job, Michael.

296
00:29:57,962 --> 00:30:01,007
You brought everything
we could ask for.

297
00:30:01,883 --> 00:30:06,554
But you can't keep men
locked away forever.

298
00:30:07,931 --> 00:30:11,935
They need fresh air,
a change of scenery.

299
00:30:12,101 --> 00:30:13,561
And....

300
00:30:17,732 --> 00:30:19,317
You understand?

301
00:30:19,818 --> 00:30:21,069
R and R.

302
00:30:23,988 --> 00:30:25,740
Rest and relaxation.

303
00:30:25,907 --> 00:30:28,743
Precisely. This is what they need.

304
00:30:28,910 --> 00:30:30,787
R and R.

305
00:30:31,996 --> 00:30:33,081
Prost,  Michael.

306
00:30:43,758 --> 00:30:45,552
Two and a half years.

307
00:30:45,718 --> 00:30:49,597
Yeah, they always go for the max.
Come on, now. They'll come down.

308
00:30:50,139 --> 00:30:52,934
PD didn't make it sound promising.

309
00:30:53,101 --> 00:30:56,104
Guy's-- He's just a burnout.

310
00:30:56,271 --> 00:30:58,773
He's trying to soften you up
for an easy deal.

311
00:30:58,940 --> 00:31:01,693
All right? There's no way
you'd do that kind of time.

312
00:31:02,485 --> 00:31:05,154
-You're goddamn right.
-You're goddamn right.

313
00:31:05,321 --> 00:31:07,407
Wait, what do you mean?

314
00:31:07,574 --> 00:31:08,825
I'm gonna bounce.

315
00:31:08,992 --> 00:31:10,618
I got places I can go.

316
00:31:11,119 --> 00:31:14,080
No. No, that's not a good idea, Huell.

317
00:31:14,497 --> 00:31:15,874
Better than going in.

318
00:31:17,834 --> 00:31:19,878
Come on, you'll have a warrant on you.

319
00:31:20,044 --> 00:31:21,546
And that shit doesn't go away.

320
00:31:21,713 --> 00:31:25,633
You know, three years from now,
you're pulled over for a broken taillight...

321
00:31:25,800 --> 00:31:27,927
...now you're not just a guy
who shoved a cop.

322
00:31:28,094 --> 00:31:31,222
You're a guy who
shoved a cop and ran.

323
00:31:31,639 --> 00:31:34,142
Well, I just won't drive
with a broken taillight.

324
00:31:34,851 --> 00:31:37,228
Sooner or later
they're gonna catch up with you.

325
00:31:37,395 --> 00:31:39,564
They didn't get D.B. Cooper.

326
00:31:46,738 --> 00:31:48,364
Why don't you--?

327
00:31:48,531 --> 00:31:51,784
Why don't you give me a shot at this?

328
00:31:51,951 --> 00:31:53,202
I think I can fix it.

329
00:31:54,203 --> 00:31:56,080
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

330
00:31:56,331 --> 00:31:59,584
What if I told you
you're not going in?

331
00:31:59,751 --> 00:32:00,877
Like, not at all?

332
00:32:01,461 --> 00:32:04,088
Not never?
Because that's what it's gonna take.

333
00:32:04,255 --> 00:32:06,049
Yeah. Never.

334
00:32:06,215 --> 00:32:08,760
All right? Just don't skip.

335
00:32:09,218 --> 00:32:12,555
How you gonna do that?
You ain't even a lawyer.

336
00:32:12,805 --> 00:32:14,432
A lawyer.

337
00:32:14,599 --> 00:32:19,228
Dude, I don't need to be
a lawyer, all right?

338
00:32:19,646 --> 00:32:21,564
I'm a magic man.

339
00:32:21,731 --> 00:32:24,067
Will you have a little faith in me?

340
00:32:38,581 --> 00:32:41,542
See, now,
I would help Huell myself if I could...

341
00:32:41,709 --> 00:32:45,213
...but I don't think he'll wait a month
for me to be reinstated.

342
00:32:45,380 --> 00:32:47,632
You've been selling drop phones?

343
00:32:47,799 --> 00:32:51,552
-On the street?
-Kim, I-- I just-- If we could....

344
00:32:52,553 --> 00:32:54,389
Look, Kim...

345
00:32:55,515 --> 00:32:56,933
...here's what I'm thinking:

346
00:32:57,100 --> 00:32:59,769
I did a little recon and
the arresting officer...

347
00:32:59,936 --> 00:33:02,105
...he has a DUI, you know,
eight years ago.

348
00:33:02,271 --> 00:33:05,149
He's been put on desk duty twice.
I know he has anger issues.

349
00:33:05,316 --> 00:33:07,777
I can attest to it, right?

350
00:33:07,944 --> 00:33:12,657
So we get him smelling like a distillery
and we piss him off in court.

351
00:33:12,824 --> 00:33:16,077
Now, he will take the bait.
He'll lose his cool in front of the judge.

352
00:33:16,244 --> 00:33:18,788
A little stumble in there
just for dramatic effect...

353
00:33:18,955 --> 00:33:22,083
...and I have some thoughts
on how to engineer that...

354
00:33:22,250 --> 00:33:23,751
...but you get the gist.

355
00:33:23,918 --> 00:33:26,546
Next thing you know, case dismissed.

356
00:33:53,114 --> 00:33:56,325
Viola, can you get me case material
for penal code 3422?

357
00:33:56,492 --> 00:33:59,370
Sections 22 to 27.

358
00:33:59,537 --> 00:34:02,040
Yeah, battery on a PO.

359
00:34:03,082 --> 00:34:04,751
Thanks.

360
00:34:04,917 --> 00:34:07,003
Great. What's our first move?

361
00:34:07,754 --> 00:34:09,380
I'm not tearing down a cop.

362
00:34:10,506 --> 00:34:11,883
That's okay.

363
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:13,426
You tell me.

364
00:34:13,593 --> 00:34:15,428
I will look into it.

365
00:34:15,595 --> 00:34:19,223
Not making any promises,
but if it is as bad as you say it is...

366
00:34:19,390 --> 00:34:21,893
...I don't know, maybe there is
something I could do.

367
00:34:22,185 --> 00:34:23,352
Maybe.

368
00:34:28,024 --> 00:34:29,901
Thanks, Kim.

369
00:34:30,068 --> 00:34:32,028
Listen, I really appreciate it.

370
00:34:33,071 --> 00:34:34,655
Okay.

371
00:34:40,703 --> 00:34:43,289
And tell me if there's anything
I can do.

372
00:34:43,581 --> 00:34:44,999
Yup.

373
00:34:48,377 --> 00:34:50,254
Oh, excuse me.

374
00:34:50,922 --> 00:34:53,007
Oh, Viola, can you just...?

375
00:34:53,174 --> 00:34:54,550
Thank you.

376
00:35:07,105 --> 00:35:08,564
I got it.

377
00:35:11,150 --> 00:35:12,652
Hope that wasn't a bribe.

378
00:35:12,819 --> 00:35:15,488
Wow, that would be one sad bribe.

379
00:35:15,655 --> 00:35:17,031
Not on my salary.

380
00:35:17,198 --> 00:35:19,575
Do you have a minute
to discuss a case?

381
00:35:20,243 --> 00:35:22,954
Sure. I got two minutes.

382
00:35:23,121 --> 00:35:25,998
I can't help but think
you guys are reaching with this one.

383
00:35:26,165 --> 00:35:28,167
Where have I heard that before?

384
00:35:28,334 --> 00:35:30,670
-Babineaux.
-Babineaux?

385
00:35:30,837 --> 00:35:32,088
Really?

386
00:35:32,255 --> 00:35:34,257
Doesn't seem like your kind of client.

387
00:35:34,423 --> 00:35:35,925
I disagree.

388
00:35:36,092 --> 00:35:38,594
To start with, the whole thing
was a misunderstanding.

389
00:35:39,345 --> 00:35:43,432
Pickpocket with a rap sheet
attacks a cop in broad daylight?

390
00:35:43,599 --> 00:35:45,143
That's a misunderstanding?

391
00:35:45,309 --> 00:35:47,520
I would not call it an attack.

392
00:35:47,687 --> 00:35:50,148
And realistically,
we should be talking misdemeanor.

393
00:35:51,232 --> 00:35:53,151
It's battery on a PO.

394
00:35:53,317 --> 00:35:55,570
-That's 18 months plus a year--
-A bitch time.

395
00:35:55,736 --> 00:35:57,947
I know what you're asking for,
it's excessive.

396
00:35:58,990 --> 00:36:00,116
He has a prior.

397
00:36:00,283 --> 00:36:02,827
-The same officer arrested him--
-Three years ago.

398
00:36:02,994 --> 00:36:06,539
But Babineaux didn't recognize him.
He didn't even know he was a cop.

399
00:36:06,706 --> 00:36:09,167
He drove an unmarked car,
he was in plain clothes...

400
00:36:09,333 --> 00:36:11,544
...he had his back turned.

401
00:36:12,795 --> 00:36:14,839
I'm sorry. I don't buy it.

402
00:36:15,006 --> 00:36:16,340
Suzanne.

403
00:36:17,550 --> 00:36:19,385
I did my homework.

404
00:36:19,552 --> 00:36:21,888
You had five cases
where civilians were accused...

405
00:36:22,054 --> 00:36:23,848
...of physical force against officers.

406
00:36:24,015 --> 00:36:28,144
Not once were the defendants given
anything close to this kind of jail time.

407
00:36:28,311 --> 00:36:30,479
They weren't repeat offenders.

408
00:36:30,771 --> 00:36:32,440
State v. Murphy.

409
00:36:32,607 --> 00:36:34,567
Murphy was homeless.
He was off his meds--

410
00:36:34,734 --> 00:36:38,362
He headbutted a police officer.
He gave him a concussion.

411
00:36:38,529 --> 00:36:40,531
Five months. Suspended.

412
00:36:40,698 --> 00:36:42,533
State v. Karp,  five months.

413
00:36:42,700 --> 00:36:45,578
-Suspended.  State v. Brezovich.
-You're not seriously compar--

414
00:36:45,745 --> 00:36:48,331
-No jail time, two months probation.
-No priors.

415
00:36:48,497 --> 00:36:52,001
Brezovich broke a cop's nose.

416
00:36:52,168 --> 00:36:54,170
This is unequal justice.

417
00:36:54,337 --> 00:36:57,256
In this case,
the officer was not injured at all.

418
00:36:57,423 --> 00:36:59,550
He was hit with a bag of sandwiches.

419
00:36:59,717 --> 00:37:02,011
How can you justify giving Babineaux
18 months?

420
00:37:02,178 --> 00:37:04,680
-Plus a year.
-He has no history of violence.

421
00:37:04,847 --> 00:37:07,141
There is no negotiation here, Kim.

422
00:37:07,642 --> 00:37:10,978
And honestly, I don't understand
why you want anything to do with this.

423
00:37:11,145 --> 00:37:14,607
On one side, I've got a decorated
police officer doing his job.

424
00:37:14,774 --> 00:37:18,152
On the other, you have a professional
thief who threw him to the ground.

425
00:37:18,319 --> 00:37:21,948
And our only witness
is a scumbag, disbarred lawyer...

426
00:37:22,114 --> 00:37:24,492
...who peddles drop phones
to criminals.

427
00:37:30,373 --> 00:37:32,541
You don't know the whole story.

428
00:37:44,804 --> 00:37:47,431
I'd rather talk to you in person.
Are you at home?

429
00:37:47,598 --> 00:37:48,808
Okay.

430
00:37:48,975 --> 00:37:50,977
Is there a good place to meet you?

431
00:37:51,269 --> 00:37:53,229
Great. I can be there within an hour.

432
00:37:53,396 --> 00:37:55,398
All right, Mr. Babineaux.

433
00:37:55,648 --> 00:37:57,525
Sure, Huell.

434
00:37:57,692 --> 00:38:00,444
Just sit tight. I'm on my way.

435
00:38:01,904 --> 00:38:05,491
I'm gonna go talk to him right now.
I need you to back my play.

436
00:38:05,658 --> 00:38:07,201
That mean what I think it means?

437
00:38:07,368 --> 00:38:11,080
He's gonna call you after I talk to him,
you and I have to be on the same page.

438
00:38:11,247 --> 00:38:13,040
Huell can't run.

439
00:38:13,207 --> 00:38:16,335
He's gonna have to put on
his big-boy pants and go to jail.

440
00:38:16,544 --> 00:38:18,671
-Shit.
-At least for a little while.

441
00:38:20,923 --> 00:38:22,133
There's no way around it?

442
00:38:22,675 --> 00:38:26,012
He's not gonna do what they're
pushing for, I promise you that.

443
00:38:26,178 --> 00:38:29,849
But yeah, no matter what,
he's gonna have to do some time.

444
00:38:30,766 --> 00:38:32,810
Well, thanks for trying.

445
00:38:32,977 --> 00:38:35,688
Jimmy, he can't jump bail.

446
00:38:35,855 --> 00:38:37,940
You'll back me up, right?

447
00:38:39,358 --> 00:38:40,860
Good.

448
00:38:42,194 --> 00:38:46,282
I mean, if you say this is the only way
we can legitimately do this...

449
00:38:46,449 --> 00:38:48,534
...well, it's the only way.

450
00:38:48,993 --> 00:38:51,287
So you're gonna tell him to stay put?

451
00:38:51,454 --> 00:38:53,414
Yeah, sure.

452
00:38:54,373 --> 00:38:56,500
You do your thing, I'll do mine.

453
00:38:56,667 --> 00:38:59,045
Jimmy, come on, what does that mean?

454
00:38:59,211 --> 00:39:00,963
Don't worry.

455
00:40:25,047 --> 00:40:28,592
Jimmy, whatever you're doing, don't.

456
00:40:30,302 --> 00:40:33,013
I know, but listen...

457
00:40:33,180 --> 00:40:35,057
...I have a better way.

